The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, April 12, 2004  LOOSE CHANGE
																								HDFC Bank has unveiled Quickremit, an online service, which enables non-resident Indians in the US to transfer money from any bank account in the US to an HDFC Bank account in India. It is available on the banks website and the sender only has to register, add details of his bank account in the US and receivers account with HDFC Bank and place an online remittance order. It gets remitted in just four working days and has low transaction fees, better exchange rates and end-to-end tracking of money along with round-the-clock customer service. 																								Doctors choice is a customised loan scheme for the practising medical fraternity that has been launched by Canara Bank. All qualified registered medical practitioners with a well-established practice or experience over three years are eligible for the loan. The maximum ceiling on the loan is Rs 10 lakh with a sub-ceiling of Rs 2 lakh.																								Tata AIG Life Insurance has launched Unit Linked Insurance Plan (ULIP) for superannuation and gratuity schemes. The ULIP Superannuation scheme provides individual members with the flexibility to allocate their money based on their risk appetite. Again, the Gratuity scheme allows the same flexibility of allocation to the employer or trustee based on their risk appetite.
